Inside the Prada store that changed how we consume fashion 

In 2001, when @prada opened its New York Epicenter inside the former Guggenheim SoHo space, the store was conceived less as a retail floor and more as an architectural environment.

Designed by Rem Koolhaas and OMA, the 23,000 square foot interior centered on the “Wave,” a 180 foot zebrawood ramp that functioned as runway, seating, and display structure.

Technology extended that shift through interactive screens providing stock and sizing information, RFID antennas tracking garments in fitting rooms, and “magic mirror” glass that could switch from transparent to opaque while displaying garments from multiple angles.

To celebrate the 25th anniversary of the store the Prada kiosk on Prince street will be distributing apples wrapped in the diagrams from the 2001 OMA project.

When David Blaine hung upside down alongside an entire Trump speech (2008)

He was demonstrating how he would perform his 60 hour hanging upside down stunt in Central Park which he would begin days later as part of his endurance performance ‘Dive of Death.’

He completed the performance but was hospitalized immediately after, citing dizziness and organ stress from prolonged inversion.

Wall writings after hurricane Katrina k*lled 1,300 people photographed by Richard Misrach

In 2005, Hurricane Katrina made landfall in Louisiana on August 29 as a Category 3 storm after rapidly strengthening in the Gulf.

Levee failures caused catastrophic flooding, leaving about 80 percent of New Orleans underwater. More than 1,300 people tragically passed and over one million residents were displaced across the Gulf Coast. 

In the aftermath, rescue teams and military units marked searched homes with spray painted symbols and dates, alongside people in search of help.

Before Lana Del Rey became a singer, she was working as a model under her birth name Lizzie Grant.

Between 2003 and 2005, she shot test photos and portfolio images while briefly signed to Ford’s development boards.

The work was limited to agency digitals and small editorial shoots, with no major campaigns tied to her. She soon stepped away from modeling to focus fully on music.
Waking a sleeping rabbit by surrounding him with tomatoes

Across a decade, photographer Julian Germain travelled to nineteen countries, photographing different classrooms.

“I think it becomes a general call to adults to think about their responsibilities towards all young people – not just their own kids. We are responsible for the world they’re growing up in. 

Despite being absent from the images, adults permeate every corner of every image. I like to think the work is confrontational; hundreds and hundreds of children and young people looking back at us with such intensity. I find that challenging.”

Throwback to Zooey Deschanel and the Millennial Optimism era (2009–2014)

Starting in indie film before moving into mainstream roles, Zooey Deschanel became one of the defining faces of early 2010s millennial optimism. 

Roles in ‘(500) Days of Summer’ and ‘New Girl’ positioned her as one of the blueprints for the era’s “quirky” archetype.

Her characters often framed adulthood as gentle and navigable, built around emotional sincerity rather than excess.

The “play bow” is a widely observed social signals observed across the animal kingdom, appearing in species that rely on play to build trust and practice survival skills.

By lowering the front of the body while keeping movement loose, animals signal that any biting, chasing, or grappling that follows is play, not aggression. 

Researchers classify it as “metacommunication,” a behavioral cue that allows rough play to happen without escalating into real conflict.

‘The Sopranos’ paintings by Sam Evans

When ‘The Sopranos’ aired in 1999, the show changed TV forever by popularizing longer story arcs rather than self contained episodic plots.

Airing on HBO gave the series freedom from advertisers and typical broadcast standards, allowing explicit content, slower pacing, and full creative control, which helped establish the show as a blueprint for modern prestige television.

via @sam_evans_art

The intricate designs of Kyiv’s pet cemetery headstones

In Ukraine, pet graves often use the same materials and production methods as human graves, including polished granite, engraved portraits, and formal name and date layouts.

Many of these headstones are made by the same monument workshops that supply public cemeteries, which is why they closely resemble human memorials.

Amongst the flirty headlines between Margot Robbie and Jacob Elordi, we remembered that Margot actually has a husband.

Her husband, Tom Ackerley, is a producer who owns LuckyChap Entertainment (co-founded with Margot), the production company working on Wuthering Heights, the movie generating these headlines.

Whether these rumors are organic or manufactured by the production company, it’s definitely great marketing for the movie.
